name: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3550
Reason: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate has a melting point that can be predicted by analyzing its structural components. The basic unit for comparison is androstane, which has a melting point of 106.5 degrees Celsius. The methyl group (–CH3) adds approximately +10 degrees Celsius due to increased molecular weight and rigidity. The oxo group (–O–) raises the melting point by approximately +5 degrees Celsius due to increased molecular weight and potential hydrogen bonding. The acetate group (–CO–) adds approximately +5 degrees Celsius due to increased molecular weight and rigidity. The presence of two fused aromatic rings increases the melting point due to increased molecular rigidity and pi-stacking interactions, estimated at approximately +25 degrees Celsius for each additional fused ring. The methyl group also increases the melting point due to increased molecular weight and rigidity.
